<title>
Cvt9/Gsa9 functions in sequestering selective cytosolic cargo destined for the vacuole.
</title>

<text>

<sections.0>
Introduction
eneral cell function and homeostasis require the regulated counterbalancing of protein synthesis and organelle biogenesis with protein breakdown and the selective degradation of organelles. he macroautophagy pathway directs the lysosome-mediated breakdown of bulk cytoplasm, including proteins, nucleic acids, lipids, and organelles and serves as the principal cellular degradative process (for review see lionsky and hsumi 1999; im and lionsky 2000). he general mechanism of autophagy has been conserved from yeast to mammals. n yeast, starvation conditions mobilize the autophagic machinery to deliver cytoplasmic constituents to the vacuole, where substrate digestion and recycling mechanisms ensure cell survival. n mammals, macro-autophagy has also been implicated to play a role in cellular remodeling during development, differentiation, and aging (ortimore et al. 1996; ittorini et al. 1999). n addition, recent findings that a dysfunctional autophagy pathway may contribute to the metastasis of certain types of cancers further underscore the relevance of autophagic degradation processes in humans (iang et al. 1999; for review see lionsky and mr 2000).
iochemical and microscopy studies have outlined the basic steps of macroautophagy in accharomyces cerevisiae (for review see lionsky and hsumi 1999). pon induction, double-membrane vesicles, termed autophagosomes, capture bulk cytoplasm before being targeted to the vacuole. usion of the autophagosome with the vacuole membrane releases a single-membrane vesicle, the autophagic body, into the vacuolar lumen. ubsequent breakdown of the autophagic body releases its cytoplasmic contents for digestion and recycling.
nsights into the molecular details of macroautophagy have been greatly facilitated through molecular genetic studies in . cerevisiae (sukada and hsumi 1993; humm et al. 1994; for review see im and lionsky 2000). he cloning of the genes that complement these yeast macroautophagy mutants, apg and aut, has subsequently led to the identification of mammalian homologues of key macroautophagy components, thus supporting the conserved nature of this pathway across eukaryotic kingdoms. he identified machinery includes a group of components required for transducing the signal for autophagy induction to downstream effectors. hief among these is the phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase homologue, or. ctivation of or represses autophagy, whereas its inhibition by nutrient starvation conditions or with the immunosuppressant drug rapamycin triggers the pathway (oda and hsumi 1998). he activity of or also affects the phosphorylation state of pg13 and the downstream kinase activity of pg1 (amada et al. 2000). or-dependent hyperphosphorylation of pg13 lessens the affinity of pg13 for the pg1 kinase and results in reduced kinase activity as well as the inhibition of autophagy. onversely, or repression leads to decreased phosphorylation of pg13, an increase in the interaction between pg13 and pg1, and the induction of autophagy.
he formation and completion of autophagosomes requires the function of a novel pg protein conjugation system which results in the covalent linkage of pg12 to pg5 (ametaka et al. 1996; izushima et al. 1998; eorge et al. 2000). he intermediate steps leading to pg12β€“pg5 conjugation involve pg7, an 1 ubiquitin activating enzyme homologue, and pg10, which functions as a protein conjugating enzyme (izushima et al. 1998; im et al. 1999; hintani et al. 1999; anida et al. 1999). fter conjugation of pg12 to pg5, the pg16 protein binds pg5 noncovalently and dimerizes to link a pair of conjugates (izushima et al. 1999). utations in any one of these components result in the failure of autophagic vesicle formation/completion. nce completed, autophagosome docking and fusion with the vacuole requires predicted vesicle fusion machinery, including the homologues of syntaxin (am3; arsow et al. 1997), -25 (am7; ato et al. 1998), and a rab-ase (pt7; im et al. 1999), as well as the class  ps protein complex (ieder and mr 1997; cott et al. 1997; ato et al. 2000; eals et al. 2000). uccessful fusion of the autophagosome with the vacuole membrane releases the single-membrane autophagic body into the vacuole lumen (akeshige et al. 1992; aba et al. 1994, aba et al. 1995). reakdown of these vesicles, which exposes the autophagic cargo for digestion and recycling, requires the acidification of the vacuole (akamura et al. 1997), as well as the vacuolar protease rb1 (akeshige et al. 1992) and the putative lipase vt17 (cott et al. 1997; eter et al. 2001).
he majority of the components required for starvation-induced macroautophagy are also employed to transport selective cargo. nder nutrient-rich conditions, the cytoplasm to vacuole targeting (vt) pathway transports the resident hydrolase aminopeptidase  () to the vacuole (lionsky et al. 1992). he overlap in transport machinery between autophagy and the vt pathway reflects the mechanistic similarities between the two pathways (arding et al. 1996; cott et al. 1996). recursor  (pr. API) is packaged in double-membrane vesicles (Cvt vesicles) that are substantially smaller than autophagosomes and appear to exclude bulk cytoplasm (Baba et al. 1997; Scott et al. 1997). Completed Cvt vesicles fuse with the vacuole and release a single-membrane vesicle (Cvt body) into the vacuolar lumen (Scott et al. 1997). The breakdown of the Cvt body releases prAPI into its resident lumenal environment, where it is proteolytically processed to the mature form (Klionsky et al. 1992).
In addition to the Cvt pathway, macroautophagy machinery is essential for the selective delivery of excess peroxisomes to the vacuole by the related pexophagy pathway (for review see Kim et al. 2000). Defects in autophagy components compromise peroxisome degradation in S. cerevisiae (Hutchins et al. 1999). In the methylotrophic yeast Pichia pastoris, vacuole-mediated degradation of peroxisomes after glucose adaptation utilizes a micropexophagic mechanism in which designated excess peroxisomes are directly engulfed by the vacuole (Tuttle and Dunn 1995; Sakai et al. 1998). Despite the difference in the site of sequestration, micropexophagy also clearly requires autophagic machinery as an increasing number of P. pastoris homologues of autophagy components are being identified (Yuan et al. 1999).
A key question that remains to be answered is what differentiates nonselelective bulk cargo from the specifically targeted cargo, such as prAPI and peroxisomes? Indiscriminate packaging of physiologically critical organelles would result in severe cellular dysfunction. On the other hand, maintaining excess organelles would be energetically wasteful, whereas the failure to sequester and degrade nonfunctional or malfunctioning organelles could result in cell death. To provide such specificity, additional factors are likely required to mediate the sequestration of particular cargo.
In this study, we have identified Cvt9 in S. cerevisiae and Gsa9 in P. pastoris, which are structural and functional homologues. Cvt9 was identified by its requirement for vacuole uptake of prAPI, and Gsa9 by its role in the turnover of peroxisomal enzymes. Although both Cvt9 and Gsa9 are required for the selective uptake of peroxisomes into the yeast vacuole for degradation, neither protein is essential for nonselective macroautophagy induced by nitrogen starvation. These proteins are associated with a unique membrane compartment located in a perivacuolar region of the cell. Our biochemical and morphological results suggest that Cvt9 and Gsa9 function to selectively sequester cytoplasmic proteins and organelles for degradation within the vacuole.
